Initial Data Wrangling/Cleaning

# Converting columns into a more usable format and selecting relevant columns
activities_analysis <- activities %>%
  mutate(Distance = Distance...17 * 0.000621371,
         ElapsedTime = `Elapsed Time...6` / 60,
         MovingTime = `Moving Time` / 60,
         AvgSpeedE = ElapsedTime / Distance,
         AvgSpeedM = MovingTime / Distance) %>%
  select(`Activity Date`, `Activity Name`, `Activity Description`, ElapsedTime, 
         Distance, MovingTime, `Max Speed`, AvgSpeedE, AvgSpeedM, `Elevation Gain`,
         `Elevation Loss`, `Elevation Low`, `Elevation High`, `Max Grade`, `Average Grade`,
         Calories)

# Time zone issues:  Converting to my time zone (PST) and having a vector for the hour of day
activities_analysis <- mutate(activities_analysis, hr_vector = ifelse(hour(mdy_hms(`Activity Date`)) <= 7,
                                               hour(mdy_hms(`Activity Date`)) + 17,
                                               hour(mdy_hms(`Activity Date`)) - 7))


# Renaming Date column
activities_analysis <- rename(activities_analysis, "Date" = "Activity Date")

# Reformatting Date column
activities_analysis$Date <- mdy_hms(activities_analysis$Date)

# Isolating the year, the day of the year, and whether or not the run was in the morning or afternoon
activities_analysis <- activities_analysis %>%
  mutate(Year = year(Date), 
         dayofyr = yday(Date), 
         AMPM = ifelse(hr_vector < 12, "AM", "PM"))

Number of Runs per Year

# nactyampm = Number of activities, by AM vs PM
nactyampm <- activities_analysis %>%
  group_by(Year, AMPM) %>%
  summarize(n = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(nactyampm) +
  geom_bar(aes(Year, n, fill = AMPM), 
           stat = "identity", 
           position = "dodge") +
  ylab("Number of Runs") +
  ggtitle("Number of Runs per Year by Time of Day") +
  labs(fill = "Time of Day") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkgoldenrod2", "darkgoldenrod4")) +
  theme_bw()

Interestingly, it seems that I have started running in the afternoons more often than the mornings as time has gone on.

From the models created, you can see that there was an increase of about 19.9 calories per minute in moving time, and an increase of about 16.7 calories per minute in elapsed time, and these results were statistically significant based on the low p-values. The R-squared values for both were also decently high, but a little lower for elapsed time than moving time. This suggests that the moving time is more of a factor when considering the amount of calories burned, which makes sense because the elapsed time will always be more than the moving time, but it varies more from run to run. The difference in elapsed time and moving time is just the time spent paused or not running. The number of calories burned during the paused times will be zero, but the elapsed time will still vary more, which is why the R-squared is a little lower. According to the Strava website, not only does moving time have an effect on the number of calories burned, but also the moving speed:

The red line is the corrected line of best fit for the outliers. The interesting thing here is the fact that the moving time p-value, before filtering out outliers, was relatively significant, but after filtering for outliers, it is not significant at all. You would think that moving time alone would be a significant factor in determining the amount of calories burned in a given run, but I suspect that there may be an interaction effect between moving time and moving speed.

caloriemodelint <- lm(Calories ~ MovingTime * AvgSpeedM, data = fastactiv)
summary(caloriemodelint)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Calories ~ MovingTime * AvgSpeedM, data = fastactiv)

## Residuals:

## Coefficients:
##                      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)           18.3325    29.7679   0.616    0.538    
## MovingTime            42.1752     0.9729  43.352   <2e-16 ***
## AvgSpeedM             -0.8559     3.9076  -0.219    0.827    
## MovingTime:AvgSpeedM  -2.8583     0.1260 -22.679   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 51.54 on 795 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9834, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9833 
## F-statistic: 1.567e+04 on 3 and 795 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The R-squared value from the Calories versus Moving Time model increased from 0.9565 to 0.9833 The interaction model suggests that an increase in one minute of moving time is associated with an increase in energy expenditure by 42.18 + (-2.86 * Average Moving Speed) calories. Likewise, an increase in one minute per mile in average moving speed is associated with an increase in energy expenditure by -0.86 + (-2.86 * Moving Time) Calories.

I was curious to see how the interaction model performs compared to just the model that calculates based on moving time and not on moving speed. I created a function in order to test the models against each other in individual cases:

calsf <- function(index) {
  p1 <- activities_analysis[index,]$MovingTime
  p2 <- activities_analysis[index,]$AvgSpeedM
  actualcalsburned <- activities_analysis[index,]$Calories
  interactionpred <- 18.3325 + (42.1752 * p1) + (-0.8559 * p2) + (-2.8583 * p1 * p2)
  movtimpred <- 19.9026 * p1
  return(data.frame(interactionpred, movtimpred, actualcalsburned))
}

rbind("400" = calsf(400), "300" = calsf(300), "100" = calsf(100))
##     interactionpred movtimpred actualcalsburned
## 400      1280.45971 1163.63868       1303.10217
## 300        36.38184   15.25866         25.67016
## 100      1070.07193 1009.06182       1013.76038

For most of the values tested, the interaction model definitely seems a lot more accurate, but for a select few, the SLR model was closer to the actual amount of calories burned. Now I wanted to compare between each run and see which method had a higher percentage of being more accurate when compared with the other.

p <- rep(NA, nrow(activities_analysis))
for (i in 1:nrow(activities_analysis)) {
  residint <- abs(calsf(i)$actualcalsburned - calsf(i)$interactionpred)
  residtime <- abs(calsf(i)$actualcalsburned - calsf(i)$movtimpred)
  if (residint > residtime) {
    p[i] <- T
  } else {
    p[i] <- F
  }
}
sum(p) / nrow(activities_analysis)
## [1] 0.2150803

It looks like for 21.51% of the runs the moving time model was more accurate than the interaction model. I think that it is safe to say that the interaction model is fairly more accurate then.
